{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_beiderbecke_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280657396/1923092901/0102.xml":{"full_text":"RETURN ON MONDAY\nTO STANDARD TIME\nStock, Bond and All Other\nMarkets End Period of\nDaylight Saving.\nBY J. C. BOYLE.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW\u2019 YORK. September 29.\u2014Busi\nness and industry throughout the\nUnited States will be less altected\nMonday by the return to standard\ntime in various communities than at\nany similar period since daylight\nsaving was Introduced. In general\nthe country communities will rejoice,\nwhile the city dwellers will view\nk the change with regret. Tho prin\ncipal activities to be uffecttd will be\nthe moving picture theaters, the\nbanks and the stock, bond and com\nmodity markets.\nAbove the mourning cry of the\ngolfer, deprived of his extra hour on\nthe links, will arise the Joyous shout\nof the movie theater manager who\nopposed the daylight saving plan as\nvigorously as the farmers.\n\"For every hour of daylight\npained In the afternoon we loae an\nhour of business.\" said one Chicago\ntheater owner today. \"In districts\nwhere children form the bulk of the\naudience the loss is greater than\nthat.\u201d\nMore Trading Expected.\nMany people In the south and west,\nwhere standard time has been ob\nserved. will feel that the change tn the\neast will remove a source of irritation\nand probably materially Increase the\ntrading in stocks, cotton, grain ana\nother commodities. In the smaller\ntowns In those sections telegraph op\nerators normally do not go to work\nuntil 8 a.m. and close their offices from\n12 to 1 p.m. As the stock and com\nmodity markets have been advanced to\nconform to the daylight saving hours\nof New York. this fact, taken In con\njunction with the difference in time in\nthe west, has deprived traders of early\nmarket news and facilities for trading\nor getting quotations. With the change\ngrain and financial markets will return\nto normal hours. This will affect, for\nexample, markets in St. Louts, New\nOrleans. Kansas City. Cleveland and\nChicago, although in the first three\ndayljght-savlng time was not generally\nused.\nTime Tablet. Out.\nIn some cities, like Rochester and\nPhiladelphia, banks and brokerage\nfirms were the only houses to observe\ndaylight saving, although in Cleveland\nthe banks remained on standard time.\nRailroads operating suburban trains\nIn and out of centers like New York,\nChicago. Boston and Phlledelphla\nhave issued revised time tables for\ntheir short-haul passenger traffic and\nexpect no difficulty In effecting the\nchange. Through trains which were\nmaintained on standard time will not\nbe affected in any way.\n\"We will put suburban trains back\non standard schedule just as easily\nas we pot them on daylight-saving\nschedule list May,\u201d said an official of\nthe Chicago and Northwestern rail\nroad. \"Not a minute will be lost and\nmlghtv few passengers will even miss\ntheir accustomed 'trains. Railroad\nemployes in the stations will be re\nlieved of a terrific amount of ex\nplaining.\"\nMean* Little In Steel Centers.\nIn the steel centers where daylight\nsaving has been in operation the\nchange to three eight-hour shifts and\nthe abolition of the twelve-hour day\nhas relieved the time schedule of any\nspecial significance. The day and\nnight operation of factories and\nplants in ,other industrials under the\nspur of increased production has had\na similar effect.\nThe change In Detroit and other\nMichigan manufacturing centers will\nmake little difference because most of\nthem run on daylight-saving time the\nyear round. During the summer months\nDetroit time is an hour slower than\nNew York, but in the October to May\nperiod it is tho same as New York in\nspite of the difference of longitude.\nDetroit Has Own Method.\nDetroit adopted daylight saving be\nfore the war. when representatives of\ntho larger industries got together and\narranged working hours so that no two\nlarge plants in the same locality begin\nor cease work at the same hour. On\nthe west side of that town, for example,\nsome plants open at 7 and others at\nfifteen-minute intervals until 9\u00bb with a\ncorresponding difference in closing.\nThis has prevented overcrowding of\nstreet cars and congestion of streets.\nWith some plants like the Ford facto\nries working three eight-hour shifts,\nthere is an almost continuous proces\nsion of men going to work and com\ning off.\nIt was found that by using daylight\nsaving continuously every workman In\n(he course of a year got an equal amount\nof daylight recreation whether he\nworked on an early or late shift. This\nwas not true under standard time.\nMore Bnjlng Predicted.\nMerchants expressed the belief to\nday that business would pick up with\nthe change, as many of their cus\ntomers from the country resented the\nhour lost when they came to the city\nto shop.\nThe sale of sporting goods, especial\nly golf equipment, is expected to fall\noff somewhat, especially in the Bos\nton section. The effect on electric\nlight and gas consumption will be\nmoderate. Only a slight increase over\nthe advance due to the shortening of\nthe autumn days is expected.\nGRAOSTREET NOTES gain\nIN WHOLESALE BUYING\nNEW YORK. September 29.\u2014Brad\nstreet\u2019s Review today says:\nWhile there is a considerable degree\nof irregularity still reported in trade,\ncrops and Industry, the general trend\nof distributive trade, responding to\nstimulating causes hitherto noted, is\nstill forward. Fall buying In wholesale\nand Jobbing lines la slightly better than\na week ago. whereas retail buying gains\nmore slowly.\nIndustry, too, shows a slight gain on\nthe whole, and collections arc rather\nbetter. Free marketing of cotton at\ngood, though not peak prices for\nthe season has given more snap to\nsouthern trade, especially in Texas.\nAtlantic seaboard states report gains in\nretail trade due to crop marketing and\nthe ending of strikes.\nCooler weather, crop marketing and\nfall festivals help western trade, and\nI\u2018aciflc coast reports are rather more\ncheerful in such lines as lumber. The\nnpparel trades, as usual at this season,\nnote especial activity, clothing-, cotton,\nwoolen and silk goods, shoes and\nJewelry noting a good volume of turn\nover.\n>ORD may soon enter\nLAKE TRANSPORTATION\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nCLEVELAND. Ohio. September 29.\n>\u2014Henry Ford will venture into lake\ntransportation If reports that he has\ntccepted bids for the building of two\nno-foot freighters for delivery In\n1924 are borne out. The boats are\nJo be used for transporting iron ore\nfrom Lake Superior ports to the Ford\nfurnaces on the River Rouge. One of\nthe vessels. It is declared, wiil be\nbullU by the American Shipbuilding\nCompany at either Lorain or Cleve\nland and the other by the Great Lakes\nEngineering Works at Ecorse yard.\nWOOL AUCTIONS END.\nLONDON. September 28.\u2014The wool\nauction sales closed today with of\nferings amounting to 7.885 bales. It\nwas a moderate assortment and was\nsteadily absorbed. The sales closed\nsteady. Coarse cross breds and In\nferior merino advanced 5 to 10 per\nqent. but Cape of Good Hope and Natal\ndeclined 5 per cent. During the series\nAmerica bought 1.000 bales, the home\ntrade, 96,000, and the continent, 96,000,\nwhile SI,OOO were held over.\nFINANCIAL.\nNEW YORK CURB MARKET\nReceived by Private Wire Direct to The Star Office\nBY WILLII.M F. DEFFEBNAN.\n'NEW YORK, September 29.\u2014The\noutstanding feature in the\nof the past week on tho curb market\nwas the Increasing reluctance to con\ntinue operations on the short side of\nthe oil shares.\nThese stocks appeared to have dis\ncounted the worst that can be known\nabout the oil Industry, and this fact*\nIs substantiated by the latest figures\non crude production.\n011 stocks were merely firm In the\nmarket today, with Standard of In\ndlana around the level of a week ago.\nIso true of Vacuum, but\nI rairle Oil and Gas, which sold ex\n,o^. YORK September 29.\u2014F01.i\"\n.i\"\u201e a 2 mcUl H*t Os bonds and\nMarket rodty th NeW Yor Curb\nBONDS,\nthousands. Rich. Low. Hose.\n4 Am Cot Oil B, ps ftTtl, ios\n\u25a0An (,H Klfc Hi.. 04% 9414 04%\nZ AMcomJs 0\u00bb 101% 10114 10114\n12 V\" 102 101% 102\nC ot U J 5%a 80% 8914 \u00a3B<4\n16 Beaverhoard Sg TO 70 70\n1 Beth Steel 7# \u201933.. 103 103 ioB\nt'o Am 8\u00bb 92 92 92\nJ 0 *erv 7, B 106 10(1 106\nV y* S rv O 80 80 80\nton* <J*\u00ab Balt sis A 103% 103% 105%\n2 Cone Textile, fr o\u00ab o\u00ab\ni Deere Co 7%,.. 09% 00% 00%\nDetroit City Gas 6a -00% 09% 00%\nDun Tire A Rah 7b 04% 04% 94%\n1 redcral Snsar (I* let 101 101\n2 Federal Siut.vr Ho 'S3 97% 07% 07%\n2 Grand Trunk \u00ab%e.. 106 106 106\n10 Libby McN L 7\u00bb. 00% 09% 09%\n1 Lie Win Lie r e 7b 102 102 102\n2 Morris A Co 7%5. 100 100 100\n3 New Or Pub Serv 3, 83% 88% 83%\n3 Pub Servos N J 7\u00bb 93% 93% 93%\n1 Hhawaheen T\u00ab 103% 103% 103%\n1 Southern Cal Ed 5b 00 90 00\nISON Y 7s 23 102% 102% 102%\nISO N Y 7k 28 104% 104% 104%\n1 S O X V 7k \u2019.SI 107% 107% 107%\n1 Colon Pacific 5b w I 99% 09% 90%\n7 Vacuum Oil 105% 105%\nFOREIGN BONDS.\n3 King of Nether Be. 07 97 07\n13 Govt of Arg 8\u00bb w 1 99% 99% 90%\n4 Swiss Govt 3%a... 09 90 00\n140 Swing Govt 3s 97% 96% 98%\n10 CS ot Mexico 45.. 34% 34% 84%\nSales STANDARD OIL ISSI\u2019BS.\nin units.\n10 Ruekeye PI 80 80 80\n1100 Hum Oil <Sr Ref new 29% 28% 29%\n273 Imp Oil of Can 09% 08 99\n3300 Inter Pot Co Ltd IB i 15% 15%\n20 Magnolia Pet 128 128 12-\n500 Nat Transit 24% 23% 28%\n10 Northern P L 103 103 105\n800 Ohio Oil new 34% 58% 54V*\n10 Prairie Oil A Gas 156% 158% 158%\n3<) Prairie P L 98% 98% 98%\n4400 S 0 lud 58% 33% 38%\nS Southern P L 120 120 120\n1100 SONY new 41 40% 41\n7 Swan Finch 23 22 28\n400 Vacuum Oil new.. 48% 45% 48%\nSales. INDEPENDENT OIL STOCKS,\nin hundred^.\nB Carib Synd 8% 8% 8%\n1 Cities Service ISO 129% 120%\nC Cities Service pfd. 66% 68% 66%\n3 Clt Serv B of* 12% 12% 12%\n82,000 Clt Serv 8 scrip.. 70 70 70\nSIOO Clt Serv Kcrlp SO 80 SO\n04 Creole Synd 1% 1% 1%\n2 Derby O K w i 6 6 6\n2 den Rock OH .78 .78 .78\n2 (Jnlf Oil of Pa 30% 30% 30%\n40 Hudson Oil 07 .06 .07\n2 Humphrey# Oil 48% 48% 48%\n280 Keystone Ranger.. .04 .03 .08\n2 Lafayette OH 1% i% i%\nS Marla ml 3% 3% 3%\n2 Mex Eagle 5% B 3%\n73 Mex OH 60 .46 .55\n1 Mex Panucc 11 1\nJ7 Mutual Oil vot cfs 9% 9% 9%\nNew Brad OH w i 4% 4 4\nCORN LEADS RISE\nIN GRAIN PRICES\nReserve Supply Low and\nFrost Damage High\u2014Oats\nand Wheat Also Gain.\nj By the Associated Press.\nCHICAGO, September 29. With\nfarm reserves of corn the smallest in\ntwenty years, except once, and with\nwet weather increasing the damage\nthat frost recently did to the new\ncorn crop, all grain has risen rapidly\nin price this week, aided to a material\nextent by reports of government plans\nfor farm relief. Compared with a\nweek ago. wheat this morning was\n2% to 4% higher, corn 4 to 7% up\nand provisions ranging from 7 decline\nto 47 advance.\nOfferings of wheat were light, and\nthe fact that hedging sales at Winni\npeg were small In proportion to re\nceipts was also a bullish influence.\nGermany\u2019s surrender In her economic\nstruggle against France had consid\nerable stimulating effect.\nThe discomfiture of traders on the\nbear side was capped by new Cana\ndian crop estimates that 1923 produc\ntion of wheat In Canada is 57.000.000\nbushels smaller than the Canadian\ngovernment\u2019s latest figures.\nIt was gossip that a noted specu\nlator was leading a bull campaign In\ncorn and oats, and that stocks of\noats were the smallest in six years.\nProvisions reflected corn strength as\nwell as better export demand.\nPENNSYLVANIA\u2019S NET UP.\nNEW YORK. September 29.\u2014Nat\nrailway operating Income of the Penn\nsylvania Railroad Company for August\nIncreased $2,142,876 over last year, last\nmonth\u2019s total being $7,774,400. Gross\nfor the month was $64,833,927. an in\ncrease of $7,463,260, while expenses\nwere $52,101,333. a gain of $4,834,188\nover last year. Freight revenues in\ncreased $6,333,480, while passenger\nrevenues Increased $1,400,558. For 1\nmaintenance of way and structure the\noutlay In August was $1,215,298 more\nthan last year, while for maintenance\nof equipment the expense increased\n$2,287,308.\nFor the eight months ended August\n31 last gross amounted to $184,735,655,\nan Increase of $79,938,983 over last\nyear, while expenses at $396,871,083\nwere $67,187,564 above the outlay for\n1922. Net railway operating Income\namounted to $66,612,012. an increase\nof $6,035,635 over the corresponding\nperiod of last year.\nFOREIGN EXCHANGE.\nSeptember 28. 1823\u201411:30 a.m.\n1 Quotations furnished by W. B. Htbba it Co.)\nNominal Selling check*\n101 l value. today.\nLondon, pound 4.8865 4.55%\nMontreal, dollar 1.00 .97%\nParis, franc 19$ .0615\nBrussels, franc 108 .0581%\nBerlin, mark .288 $8.50 per billion\nRome, lira 193 .0457%\nZurich, franc 193 .1788\nAthens, dnfehma 193 .0163\nMadrid, peseta 198 .1858\nVienna, crown 2926 .1*10614%\nBudapest, crown 30-0 SSf 3\nPrague, crown -92 ti\nWarsaw, mark -288 -V2lV 3\nCopenhagen, crown 208 .1793\nChristiania, crown ~MB 169.1\nStockholm, crown 268 .2657\nBv the Associated Prc\u00df*.\nNEW YORK, September 29.\u2014Foreign\nexchanges irregular (quotations In\nUnited States dollars). Great Britain,\ndemand 4 64%; cables. 4.55%; sixty\nday bins on banks 4.52. France de\nmind. .0614%; cables. 0615. Italy,\ndemand .0466%; cables, .9457. Bel\ndemand. .0522%; cables. .05i$.\nGermany, demand. .0000000066; cable.,\n0000000065. Holland, demand, .8933;\ncables. .3933. Norway, demand, .169 L\nSweden, demand. .2849. Denmark, de\nmand .1787. Swltserland, demand.\n1785 Spalti. demand, .1368. Greece,\ndemand. .0165. Poland, demand. .000003.\nCzechoslovakia, demand, .0300. Jugo\nslavia, demand, .0112. Austria, de\nmand. .000014. Rumania, demand.\n0046%. Argentina, demand. .3560.\nBrazil, demand. .1000. Montreal, de\nmand, .97%.\nTHE EVENING STAR, WASHINGTON, D. C.. SATURDAY 1 SEPTEMBER 29, 1923:\ndividend |2-during the week. wa\u00bb up 3%\npoints from last Sa.urday\u2019s closing.\nSeveral new Industrial issues were\n.admitted to trading In the past few\ndays, but were welcomed with only\nBlight consideration by the outside\npublic.\nThe recent advance of 3 points In\nSpringfield Body was followed by- the\nofficial statement that the company\nhas $1,000,0*0 In orders on the books,\nwhich Is sufficient to keep plant* op\nerating at capacity for at least six\nmonths\nHopeful statements regarding cop\nper have been reflected in a slight inr\ncrease In the demand for copper\nctocks. but price changes have been\nunimportant.\nOhio Copper was a leader of this\ngroup and was up about 10 points on\nthe week.\n2 Omar OH A Oan.. .61 .61 .61\n13 Penn Beaver OH.. .53 .39 .58\n14 Roy Can OH Ref 8% 3 8%\n1 Balt Ck Prod new.. 17% 17% 17%\n7 Hap,Hr# Rcfln 1% 1% 1%\n1 Seaboard Oil 1% 1% 1%\n26 Sou States Oil ...-15% 14% 15%\n10 Turman Oil 66 .63 .63\nINDUSTRIALS.\n2 Acme Coal new 1% 1% 1%\nlAm Multigraph, Co 21% 21% 21%\n2Ar*Co of Del* pfd M\u00bb% 88%. 80%\n1 Atlantic Fruit w 11% 1% 1%\n4 Bridgeport Mch w I 10% 10% 10%\n10 Brit-Ara Tob Gou.. 25 24% 25\n3 Brit-Am Xo Co ref 25 23 25\n1 Brit lot Corp A.. IS 18 l\u00ab\n3 Dklyo City BR 10% 10% 10%\n6 Buddy Budi 1A 1A 1 A\nIJ Cent Terca* pfd... 4 4 4\n3 Ontrlfug Iron Pipe 20 19% 20\n6 Dublller C A Radio 10% 10 10%\n1 Durant Motor 29 20 29\nIDu Pont Motors 8% 8% 8%\n1 El Bond A Sh nfd 97 97 97\n1 Glen Allen Coal.. 72% 72% T 2%\n4 Gleaaonlte Prod ..9% 9% 9%\n3 Goodyear Tire 10% H>% 10%\n2 Gold Dual w 1.... 20 JH> 20\n1 Imp Tob Canada... 6 6 6\n5 Int Concrete 9% 0% 9%\n1 Kreage 85 33 85\n1 Kuppen B A Co pM *3 83 85\n5 Mesa hi Iron 5% 6%\n1 Nat Sup Co of Del 56% 66% 56%\n1 Radio t\u2019orp 8% 8% 3%\n1 Reading Coal rts wl 20% 20% JO%\n3 Reo Motor 16% 16% }f*%\n10 Ho C A 1 new 12 .12 .12\n2 SpHnafleld Body Co 19 18% 19\n1 Htadebaker Wlf Rb 51% 51% 51%\n1 Htuta Motor 18% .I*% -I?. 1\nX Swift Co 102 102 102\n2 Technical Ptod 5% 5% 5%\n1 Unit Prof Sh new. 5% 5% 6%\n1 Unit Retail Candy\u2019 5% 5% 5%\n1 Unit Show Mach Co 35% 85% 85%\nMINING.\nB Alaska-Brit Colo .70 .70 .70\n1 Alvarado Min 1% -1% 1%\n1 Amal Lead Zinc 8m 4% 4% 4%\n800 ArlrooK Globe Cop, .15 .13 .16\n10 Bntta a Western .25 .25 .25\nS Canano Copper 144 144 144\n1 Con Cop Min tun cf 1% 1% 1%\n140 Cartes Sliver 45 .42 .45\n5 Crown Reserve 5! .38 .58\n6 Crown King 1% 1% 1%\n20 Eureka Croeaua .66 .08 .06\n\u202240 Fortune Mines .07 .06 .07\nSO Goldfield Deep Mine .12 .12 .12\n1 Goldfield Florence.. .59 .39 .39\n20 Goldfield Jackpot 49 48 48\n60 Hill Top Nevada.. .05 ~05 .05\n1 Heel a Mine 7% 7% 7%\n3 Homeetake Ext 1 .90 .90\nSO Independence Lead. .93 .32 .32\nI Kerr Lake 2% 2% 2%\n20 Lone Star 08 .02 .03\nSO National Tin 12 .11 .12\n6 New Dominion Cop. 3 2% S\n180 Nixon Nevada .01 .01 .01\n9 Nlplialng 5% 5% 5%\n24 Ohio Copper 72 .68 .70\nHO Red Hill Florence.. .06 .05 .06\n30 San Toy 04 .04 .04\n10 Spearhead Gold .12 .12 .12\n1 Tonopah Belmont.. .58 .58 .58\n10 Tonopah Divide .44 .44 .44\n3 Tonopah Extension. 2 2 2\n8 Tonopah Min 1% 1A 1A\n12 United Eastern 1(4 1% 1%\n10 C 8 Contin new wl .20 .20 .20\n2 Wenden Copper .75 .74 .75\n10 West Utah 82 .32 .32\n\nCOMMODITY NEWS\nWIRED STAR FROM\nENTIRE COUNTRY\nDETROIT. September 29.\u2014Tha au\ntomobile Industry is watching closely\nfor the results of today\u2019s announce\nment of a new Oldsmobile light six\ncylinder car at a very low prise. Au\ntomobile manufacturers who recently\nreduced prices are almost unanimous\nIn declaring that the cuts do not sig\nnify prloe war, hut represent econ\nomies In manufacturing or lower ma\nterial co r ts.\nATLANTA, September 29.\u2014Georgia\ncane growers will market their larg\nest production of ayrup this fall.\nPrices are good and there is little\ncompetition.\nPORTLAND, Ore., September 29.\nMontana hard wheat flour has ad\nvanced to $7 a barrel, while bakers\u2019\nblue stem ha* been reduced 5 cents\nmore than was anticipated, to $6.60.\nPastry flour has been pushed up 20\na new top of $5.90.\nST. PAUL* September 29.\u2014The Cut\nGlass Manufacturing Corporation will\nbuild a new plant here at a cost of\n$75,000. The expansion may Involve\na still larger investment, as a new\ndeposit of high-grade sand has been\ndiscovered near High Dam, and It is\nreported Henry Ford contemplates\nsecuring his glass for oar production\nfrom the n\u00abAv plant\nMADISON. Wla. September 29.\nThe Wisconsin potato warehouses\nhave openefF for fall buying. The\nmarket is short and good prices are\nprevalent. Few farmers have begun\nto dig, but the crop Is due to move\nin large volume next week.\nTULSA, Okla., September 29.\u2014A tre\nmendous falling off In tho production\nof Oklahoma crude oil was recorded\nlast week. The dally average output\nwas 20,267 barrel* less than for the\nweek previous\nRECEIVER IS APPOINTED\nFOR VIM MOTOR TRUCK\nBy the Awociated Press.\nPHILADELPHIA. September 29.\nFederal Judge McKeeh&n has ap\npointed Kern Dodge temporary re\nceiver of the Vim Motor Truck Com\npany) Inc., on a bill In equity filed by\nA. V. W. Surre of New York, a credit\nor for $6,000. The company consented\nto the receivership. Its assets were\nplaced at $2,468,081 and its debts at\n$1,301,277, with an additional $650,000\ncapital stock liability.\nThe bill In equity declared the com\npany was solvent, but lacked work\ning capital.\nDURANT IN NEW MOVE.\nMotor Acceptance Company to Act\nas Brokers.\nDOVER, Del., September 29.\u2014A\ncharter was Issued by the state de\npartment today to the Durant Motor\nAcceptance Corporation, having a\ncapital of 2,000,000 shares without\nnominal or par value. The Incor-\nR orators are W. C. Durant. Deal,\nJ.; Carroll Downes, Narbeth, Pa.,\nand C. F. Daley, New York city.\nThe company. It is understood, is\na subsidiary of the Durant Motor\nCompany. The purpose of the new\nconcern, according to Its application,\nIs to aid in the manufacture of auto\nmobiles and to act as brokers.\nBOSTON STOCK MARKET.\nBOSTON, September 29.\u2014Following\nis a list of today s highest, lowest and\nclosing prices for the most active stocks\ndealt In here:\nHigh. Low. Close.\nArcadian Coos 1% 1% 1%\nArisen* Com 8% 8% 8%\nCalumet A Arisons 47 47 47\nCalumet a Heels 30% 20% 20%\nCanon BUI Hln 8% 8%\n*8\nEastern 88 82 82 88\nMaasarhaaetta Oa* 18 18 IB\nMayflower 0 O 2% 2%. 2%\nMohawk 88 38 38\nNational Leather 8% 8% 8%\nNeV Cornell* 17% 17% 17%\nNorth Witte 1% 1% 1%\nPacific Mills 87% 87% 87%\nHhoe Machine 35% 35% 83%\nSwift A Co 101% lOt 101%\nBwlft International 18% 18% 18%\nVentura Oil 22 22 22\nWalworth 15% 15% 16%\nWolverine 8%\nBusiness Outlook Is Now Main\nConcern of 'Domestic Markets\nConditions Vary Widely in Different In\ndustries\u2014Ruhr Reports Most Impor\ntant Outside News of Week.\nBY STUART P. WEST.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Btar.\nNEW YORK, September 29.\u2014There\nhave been few developments In the\ngeneral business situation\u2019during the\npast week. The stock market has of\nfered, on the whole, more resistance\nto efforts to force It down. As prices\nhave drawn near the low level reach\ned, once In the first week of July and\nagain In the first week of August,\na greater degree of stability has been\nshown.\nThe most important outside event\nwas the final announcement thaf Ger\nmany had given up passive resistance\nin the Ruhr. The military dictatorship\nat the moment has quieted fears ot a\ncommunist uprising. French and Bel\ngian currencies rose sharply to the\nbest figures reached sincp the middle\nof June. Foreign government bonds\nwere favorably Influenced, for a time,\nbut in the end gained no ground as\ncompared with a week ago.\nSltnatloa Abroad Still Involved.\nIn fact, outside the exchange mar\nket, in which there was an extended\nshort interest to reckon will), the\nRuhr surrender has scarcely counted\nas a factor. Tho reason is that the\neequel. so far as regards the repara\ntions problem and European rehabili\ntation. is quite us much in doubt as\never. The way in now open for France\nto prove her contention that Germany;\nis quite able to pay in full. Or the i\nresult may be to demonstrate, .as the;\nEnglish believe and as moat outside\neconomists feel too, that any attempt\nto compel the acceptance of the max-\nImum Indemnity, and start collect-1\nIng It, will fall because it will\nthreaten breakdown of the German 1\nIndustrial structure.\nDeadlock Over Steel Prices.\nThe main concern in the home\nmarkets is still the business outlook j\nin this country. As was said a week I\nago. this Is a subject which cannot 1\nbo treated as a whole. In some lines\nconditions aro profitable, In others\nthey are not. The deadlock remains\nunbroken between buyers and sellers\nof steel, the former disposed to hold\noff as long as possible before agree\ning to pay prices which represent a\n10 per cent average advance over\nwhat they have been paying on old\ncontract*. The outcome will he either\nthat the steel companies will begin\nto cut prices In their efforts to stimu\nlate new business or that consumers\nwill come In at the present level,\nrather than let their supplies run\ndown to the danger point as they did\na year ago.\nThe position Is not satisfactory in\nthe metal trade* and some producers\nof atno and lead have shut down rath\ner than operate where they cannot\nmake money. The cotton nYHIs are\nholding oft to see what effect the new\ngovernment report on cotton will\nhave upon quotation* for the staple.\nOn the other hand, with the rise In\nsugar prices, carrying them not far\nfrom the high of the year, the pros\npects for this industry are bright.\nThe same Is true of the tobacco trade\nBEARS POUND WEAK\nSPOTS ON EXCHANGE\n4\nWeek Also Secs Better Ee\u00abpon\u00bbe to\nConstructive News\u2014B. 0.\nDividend Big Factor.\nBy tb* Associated Prea*.\nNEW YORK. September 29.\u2014Stock\nprices made a better response this\nweek to constructive news, but spec\nulators for the decline continued to\nattack various sections of the list,\nand succeeded In uncovering a num\nber of weak spots. Bond prices\nmoved within narrow and irregular\nlimits, with a better demand noted\nfor some of the eastern and middle\nwestern railroad Hens.\nOne of the outstanding domestic\ndevelopments was the resumption of\ndividends on the common stock of\nthe Baltimore and Ohio railroad.\nThis brought about sympathetic ad\nvances In other railroad shares, buy\ning being Influenced also by another\nreport of weekly car loadings In ex\ncess of 1,000.000 cars and a series of\nfavorable August earnings state\nments.\nThe first thirty-nine clast one roads\nto report showed combined net In\ncome of $6M18.000, as compared with\n$51,412,000 In July and $27,917,000 In\nAugust of last year.\nOfficial abandonment ,of passive re\nsistance In the Ruhr hkd a tonic ef\nfect on the foreign exchangee, par\nticularly those of the continental al\nlies. but the gains were modified\nlater by serious political action In\nB Weekiy steel trade reviews reported\nslight quickening In Interest, while\nthe United States Steel Corporation\nreported an Increase In operations\nfrom 87.8 to 90.8 per cent. Sugars\nmoved to higher ground in sympathy\nwith higher commodity prices. To\nbaccos also were strong on reports\nof increased production and s\u00bbie\u00bb-\nHeaviness of the motors reflected the\nspeculative fear of Intense competi\ntion next year.\nWEEK SEES SLUMP\nIN BUTTER MARKET\nlighter Bemad With DecteMe in\nReceipts and Increase in\nStorage Supplies.\nBy the Aaaoclatad Proas.\nCHICAGO, September 29.\u2014 Sharp de\nclines featured the unusually weak\nbutter market during the week, prices\nat the four principal markets taking\ndrops ranging from 1 to 3Vi cents.\nOverconftdano*. which ha> carried\nthe market higher during the sum\nmer, was given by operators as the\nr\u00aba\u00abon.\nProduction reports Indicate that the\ndecrease In the make has been check\ned. and surplus supplies are reported.\nReceipts showed a decrease and\nstorage holdings showed an increase,\ncaused by the movement of surplus\nstocks to storage. A decrease In con\nsumptive demand was considered tp\n**There were no arrivals of foreign\nbutter at New York during the week.\nRange and closing prices, wholesale,\n92 score butter were as follows:\nChicago, 3% less at 44; New York,\n2 less at 46%; Boston. 1 less at 46%;\nPhiladelphia. 1% leas at 46%.\nNICKEL PLATE\u2019S NET UP.\nCLEVELAND, Ohio, Septerobsr 29.\nReporta filed with the Interstate Com\nmerce Commission covering operation\nof the Nickel Plate railroad for the\nmonth of August shows a net railway\noperating Income of $1,007,992, an In\ncrease of $178,637 over the same\nmonth a year ago, company officials\nannounced today. For the eight\nmonth period ending August 31 the\nnet railway operating Income was\n$7 671,118, an Increase of $1,029,067\nover the same period for 1921\nand of t]ie chain stores and other re- i\ntall organizations.\nIt Is also apparent that when It j\ncomes to considering the outlook for\nthe Wall street markets, the same\ndistinction mupt be observed between j\ngroups of securities that Is found In j\n\u00bbn analysis of their corresponding\nindustries. This has shown al\nready during the last week or two\nIn the highly irregular price move\nment, stocks like the sugars, the to-\nbaccos and the electrical company\nshares having gained, while shares\nof the automobile, the rubber and tire j\ncompanies and the steels having most j\nof them lost. Taking the general\nbusiness volume, the enormous haul\novqr the railroads la a trustworthy\ncriterion. Added to this is the state-\nment by the mercantile agencies that\nthe main drift of distributive trade\nIs upward and that tt compares favor- j\nably with a year ago.\nPcMStmlaiii Not Justified Yet.\nIf the pessimism which is still up-\npermost In Wall street professional\ncircles is to be justified, It will be i\nbecause of changes in the trade situ\nation of which so far there are no\nsigns. Asked for reasons \\#iy stocks\nshould go down from what Is almost\nthe lowest level of the year, the\nanswer is that before long curtail\nment of demand will become more\npronounced and that producers will\neither have to cut their output or re\nduce prices, with the result that com\npany earnings will decline.\nThis and the approaching session of\nCongress, with the presidential cam\npaign looming ahead, are the main\npoints of the present \"bear\" position\nOn the other hand, practically every\nrepresentative of big business who\nhas spoken publicly has expressed\nconfidence in the future, taking his\nstand on the extraordinary strength\nof the credit structure and the ab-.\nsence of Inflation and overproduction,\nwhich are the familiar antecedents of\na period of depression.\nRelief In Sight for Wheat Farmer.\nThe latest proposals for dealing with\nthe plight pf the wheat farmer are\nmuch more conservative than any\nmade so far. The American wheat\nraiser finds it difficult, with anything\nlike normal crops in other countries,\nto meet the competition in the foreign\nmarket of other exporting nations.\nTherefore, he must look to the home\nmarket chiefly, protected as it is by\na high tariff duty. The latest sug\ngestion, coming from the northwest\nenr states, is that this could be dope\nsuccessfully by a government super\nvising body, which would tell the\nfarmer how much of his land could\nbe safely devoted to wheat, and how\nmuch should be given over to other\ncrops. This is the sensible way to\ndeal with a state of things which has\nbeen brought about by excessive pro\nduction.\nThe business community rejects the\nidea of artificial price fixation. In\nvolving use of the public funds for\nthe benefit of a single class. It is\ngratifying to note that the committee\nrepresenting bankers, farmers and\ncongressmen from six of the leading\nnorthwestern states, who discussed\nthe matter with the President this\nweek, came out against thLs false and\ndangerously unfair principle.\nSTANDARD OIL BUYS\nOKLAHOMA LANDS\n$8,000,000 Involved in One of\nv Largest Transactions in\nRecent Years.\n\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nTULSA. Okla., September 28. \u2014One\nof the largest oil land transactions in\nrecent years has just been concluded\nhere by the sale of all producing\nacreage In the Burbank pool and in\nOsage, Washington, Rogers and No\nwata counties, Okla., and Greenwood\ncounty, Kan., owned by the Waite-\nPhlllips Company. The purchaser was\nthe Mid-Kansss Oil and Gas Com\npany. a subsidiary of the Standard\nOil of Ohio. The price was aboiH\n$8,000,000. Nearly 10.000 barrels daily\nproduction Is involved, mostly from the\nBurbank pool.\nLIVERPOOL COTTON.\nLIVERPOOL September 29.\u2014Cotton\n\u2014Spot in fair demand: prices steady;\ngood middling, 17.45; fully middling.\n17.33; middling, 17.13; low middling,\n16.68; good ordinary, 16.18; ordinary,\n15.88. Sales, 3.000 tfale, including 1,300\nAmerican. Receipts, 6,000 bales, no\nAmerican. Futures closed quiet. Sep\ntember. 17.08; October, 16.39; Decem\nber, 16.95; January. 16.74; March.\n15.60; May, 15.26; July, 14.86. Official\nnoon closing. September. 17.08 value.\nMoney to Loan\nSecured by lint deed of tract no real estate.\nPrevailing interact and commisaton.\nJoseph I. Weller\nOver 42,606 Depositors Capital and Surplus, $2,006,090\ns;\nAsk about our Banking-by-Mail facilities when you\ncome in to make your pay-day deposit. We furnish\nnecessary stationery, envelopes, etc.\nDeposits Invited in Any Amount; Same Rate of\nInterest Paid on Small and Large Accounts\nOpen Until 5:30 P.M. Monday and Tuesday\nOFFICERS: DIRECTORS:\n.WILLIAM D. HOOVER ....Proaldeot Woodbury Blair William D. Hoover\nWOODBURY BLAIR ....lat V. Pro*. Jame* A. Buchanaa Reginald 8. Haidckoper\nFRANK W. STONE ....2d V. Pro*. William A. B. Church Victor Kauffmans\nFRANK STETSON Trust Officer Walter C. Clephane Charles Uinaball\nCHAB. C. LAMBoBN Treasurer H. Rosier Dulany, Jr. Edmund 